The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator who'd make the classics cheap.
Maybe it won't be long.
About the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have written on Mobil.cz many times.
This was confirmed by ČTÚ, who pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in us than in the rest of the Union.
Following recent steps by the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to go to war.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, but we have three mobile networks and a penetration of over 100 percent.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to say that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often the case with the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, who has stated several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
I guess it's true that a classic operator with his own network doesn't seem to have too many chances anymore (otherwise, he'd probably have a hard time looking for frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual operator.
The entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a significant reduction in prices to which classical operators had to react.
However, even before Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those of us in the UK sounded.
However, it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be truly successful.
Besides, we don't have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you of the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Meanwhile, the Penta financial group, which owns U:phone in the Czech Republic, is behind Mobilking.
The advantage of virtual operators is to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they need much less customers than a classical operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators tend to profile themselves as low-cost operators - offering cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the United Kingdom offers at least half the cost of SMS to its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, there can be a pretty good move and a bet on an untraceable target group.
Because this operator is specifically targeting men.
"The right guys choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It's hard to say if a concept like that could be captured in Poland with us.
Vodafone Press Speaker Miroslav Čepický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of service supply."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, mobile operators say
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look too hopeful.
Rather, there will be a launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," she said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studnicková, press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
She thus directly confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to do so.
Rather, they try to do everything to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
For a long time, the GTS Novera group has not been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator, so it would like to take another step to become a real competitor of the O2 Telephony in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only solid but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have already made progress in the negotiations," said press spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Well, maybe it's coming to a better time.
It seems from unofficial information that the first virtual operator should be waiting for us by the end of the year.
For now, however, its origin is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far we have not been contacted by any subject with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň, of the O2 Telephony Press Department, said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Press spokesman T-Mobilo Martina Kemrová adds in rare line with O2: "We have not yet recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further."
And he adds, "It's hard for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table to be able to think in this short horizon."
Vodafone is more likely to be able to meet the requirements of his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial in terms of customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The process of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, leading to a decrease in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when it comes to operators, they are able to pull a rope, they also testify to pulls around the formation of U:phone.
Probably the biggest pressure towards CTÚ went to the time of the U:phone from T-Mobile.
This is demonstrated by publicly available information from the website of the Czech Republic.
Now, however, it is U:phone that fits as an argument why a virtual operator is not allowed.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would make high demands on him and his services in particular."
In view of this approach of mobile operators, however, the total lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is directly striking.
It is not only the position of the Czech Republic, which, unfortunately, does not have the power to intervene in competition, unlike the United Kingdom and other developed countries.
These belong exclusively to the Competition Protection Office (UOHS).
But he took his typical stand on the whole issue.
"The entry into the mobile market of a virtual operator would be possible once a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual operator for the lease of the necessary infrastructure would be concluded.
No such contract has been concluded so far, since the offer of potential bidders was probably not sufficiently interesting for classical operators," Kristian Chalupa, of the ÚOHS External Relations Department, said in an answer to our question.
I don't think he's going to be surprised by the operative representatives.
It is more than a level playing field from the Office, which is intended to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country where virtual operators usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of mobile phone prices."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices is clearly not in the interest of the UOHS.
In fact, shocking on the whole case is the impression of the three mobile operators, which comes from their reactions.
The question, if it really is just a coincidence, is offered entirely by itself.
Just as the exact price of gasoline in pump stations is certainly only part of a coincidence and a hard competitive fight.
"The government has not found any signs of anti-competitive action in this matter and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore has an appropriate increased responsibility for their market behaviour.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are likely to be met by the telecommunication regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the CTTO, according to which telecommunications are the only market in terms of competition.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And a mobile operator - it makes a lot of sense - to its monopoly network.
So in a certain segment, it has to be dominant.
Even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least warning to the UOHS that three mobile operators are doing the same.
However, the complaints of a number of applicants (including GTS Novera mentioned) show that very similar obstacles are encountered by all operators when dealing with them.
The weighting of the responsibilities of the CTTU is then a relatively common trick in telecommunications, which the UOHS gives away from the whole issue.
We've met him in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the telecommunications law, the extension of the powers of the CTTO to competition in telecommunications has failed, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS must know more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It works when no one's looking.
In spite of this, the operation of some pseudovirtual operators, which exist in Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
They are companies issuing their own mobile phone prices, which are only part of the public.
It's usually a multi-level marketing company.
His own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others.
Prices of these companies usually only get to the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company faces the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer then gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar resales.
"If there are cases that you are talking about, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would deal with and could arise in the end of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemr answered our question about this problem.
However, it is unlikely that similar activities would be carried out against responsible people from mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators, however, are prevented from doing so.
Because of the activities of these companies, they have negligible profits and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law of similar speculation allows, however, the services of these companies use only a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it fully as normal customers of mobile operators."
But that should be at least weird.
In addition, another question for the UOHS is being opened.
If mobile operators close their eyes above the same procedure, why block the creation of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the OOHS has relatively strong powers to detect similar activities, and if it does not want to, it does not need to be satisfied with the operator's explanation that they have no idea of anything like this and their business conditions prohibit it.
When We Won't Be Most Expensive
As the text has already fallen several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a marked drop in prices for services.
In virtually every country where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to defend them more or less.
Jimi's arguments used were practically identical - too small, if not too saturated market, problems with quality of services, etc.
In advanced countries, however, regulatory authorities have affected not the interests of mobile operators but their customers in these moments.
Whether through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator had been created and others were wrapped up in it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing the whole case over like a hot potato.
We cannot get rid of our experience of the impression that confusion in competences is more appropriate in these cases than it is.
But let's not throw flint in the wheat.
If behind-the-season information is correct and the virtual operator really soon appears with us, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators has allowed the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will only be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling the alarm than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to four implementations of a new version of the Czech state anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented the new recordings of the state anthem where my home is.
The hymn was re-recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bjelohlavek.
There are four versions - male or female solo singing, in congregational application and instrumental text.
