Prague MHD takes the chip for the first time on Wednesday
On Wednesday, 1 October 2008, the Prague Transport Company will be registered as the date on which the first passengers will enter the metro, trams and buses who will have an electronic ticket in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At this point, he can get about a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual ticket (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have to record on their chip card in the info centres and workplaces of the Transport Company at the subway stations Museum, Mostek, Holešovice Station, Angel, Rostyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Paradise Garden, Kačerov and Luka.
Since yesterday, coupons can also be purchased via the Internet on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by over four hundred customers in the afternoon.
Those who start using Internet commerce can definitely forget the outlet windows at metro stations, where they have to regularly stand in long queues for paper tickets.
The buyer will buy it online and they will record it on the Opencard card in one of the 13 offices of the City Library.
"At these places, the passenger has a barrier with a trained service, which will help interested people with internet purchases and will also record on their card a purchased coupon," said Project Speaker Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries you will be able to record electronic coupons on Opencard also in self-service vending machines, which are installed in several metro vests.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, they resemble ticket markers and passengers may already have noticed them at Rostila, Budějovicka, I. P. Pavlova, Florence and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are now five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," he added.
Kupon will check the driver's location of the machine
The maintenance of machines that start working tomorrow is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will be recorded on it itself.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
In suburban trains and bus lines with numbers 300 to 499, the main inhabitants of the Central Bohemian municipalities travel to the capital.
"In trains included in the Prague Integrated Transport, guides are equipped with card readers to determine the time and band validity of coupons," explained Philip Drápal of the Ropid organization, which forms the driving order of the Prague Public Transport.
The suburban buses have card readers built in the cash register by the driver.
On arrival it is therefore necessary not only to show the driver the chip card, but also to attach the Opencard to the designated place on the side of the register.
The driver will check the validity of the recorded coupons.
"If passengers need to verify the validity of recorded coupons, nothing is easier than asking drivers for this information," Drápal added.
Travelers who do not drive suburban buses and do not remember when their coupon expires may go back to self-service machines where tickets are recorded.
Here, information on the validity of their documents will be displayed on the display of the device.
