Pride and Obstacles to the Life of Blacks in a Separate City
Hidden among the vast amusement parks of the larger Orlando, several miles from everything shiny, noisy and brown, lies a quiet city in which the pride and intensity of African American life live.
Eatonville, the first fully black city that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquet playgrounds, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough quayawa, two schools and no prison."
Now it's a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Tony Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Festival of Zora! to present a gift to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a party, even though she made it a tourist stop by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers project during the economic crisis.
It's still so independent, dignified and private, as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and did not share their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's losing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on race, many locals remain wary of foreign views.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It's got to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of the Black Rise and a community of almost 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is double compared to the national average.
It is the centre of literature, but also oak-shadowed example of the rural rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - which originated from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the inhabitants here are both proud and protective.
And concerns about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She presented her hometown to the world through the heartful books of the Rivers as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs of the Florida tourist guide changed the city to road No. 17, which leads through the often missed centre of Florida, into the stage of black history and human drama.
With the destruction of the big drum in life and in literature, Hurston's readers were brought to the store by First Eatonville Mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courts and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the new widow Dash's husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sold drinks of all kinds and anything that fits the clock hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston Eatonville linked to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This clearly wasn't the typical Fodor's publishing company.
In fact, it wasn't a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it as it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chipper exterminator who often returned after her family moved to Florida Jacksonville.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she arrived in the city, she arrived without an announcement in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of decent clothes today.
Most of the residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but a lot of them were squirming.
"People always liked to see Zora," Franklin said.
But, he added, swinging on the chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were cut off from the press.
She seemed to be forgotten by Eatonville and the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 20th century, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had lived before.
In Eatonville, there were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings.
"I don't think they understood her meaning for the world or her reference at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's biography "Wrapped in Rainbows" published in 2003.
The change came in the '80s of the 20th century.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch the city along a five-way highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-way main road.
The break-up of Orlando has already pushed interstate highway No. 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still coming from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950 ’ s, he brought the struggle to stir hate races to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and things at people who were sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"We actually had a lady here who killed her.
They threw a melon out of the car."
In a letter to The Orlando Sentinel in 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's requirement of forced integration and his decision in the Brown versus the Chamber of Education case stated that "it is more offensive to my race than to celebrate."
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the youth here.
"Black children were used to hug - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the non-profit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
It took a while for teachers and pupils to come from the same place, she added.
"You're not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural barrier there," said Miss Nathir.
Civil rights, however, helped create space for many more Zora Neal Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, have risen above prejudices with reckless confidence and feelings such as "How can someone deny the delight of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker traveled to the unmarked grave of Hurston and began to fight for the revival of her reputation.
Five years later, he came to the bookshelves in the bookshelves of the famous Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway, who reintroduced it into the American canon.
The highway project came just as the most famous daughter of Eatonville found the lights of the ramp again.
The former neighbors of Hurston now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to his highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inauguration event two years later, and each January many return to the celebration.
After a few years, he resigned from the highway project.
"The five power lines of the highway have risen, you would say it has set off a real civil pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd said it more simply, "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Extracurriculars like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the church here in 1993, began to appear in more numbers, and residents began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville joined the national historical register in 1998.
The new one-storey library (named after Hurston, of course), was opened in 2006 at the newly embellished and decorated Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a dead end in summer rain, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1980s.
(Today it's 90 percent black.)
Strange people who come to look for the story and meaning of Eatonville are often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is necessary to have in advance and certain things - like wall paintings in the oldest Eatonville church, painted by whites and displayed by blacks in the fields - should not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, such as Jones, a courageous, self - confident teacher who likes to eat red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
Even so, as the Hurston Festival increased, domestic pride also increased.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston has seen her entire race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, and just as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnics.
The voice of Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, sounds like genuine love for the community when he plans to return to Eatonville after high school to work in the local government or the police, who he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as 11 - year - old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Cannon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just drive by, think, 'Hmm, this town is nothing against the others,' said Alondra Kenon recently on Sunday after church.
"But if you really stop and look into history for a while, it's a very nice city."
