Interview - Blood That Is Safe Again
Hema-Quebec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the founding yesterday and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly pleased, as Hema-Quebec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained confidence in the public, who, after a scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s, was seriously shaken.
As is generally known, the state reserve of blood administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated during the 1980s by the immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and a wave of public opposition, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994 chaired by Judge Horace Krever to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy and to recommend that such a disaster should no longer be repeated.
While Judge Krever gave up his report, some provinces put forward a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québek, Géline's committee played this role.
Following Gélineau and Krevere's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, who was supposed to run Québec, and the Canadian blood company to supply all the provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Québec began his activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was crippling.
Through systematic efforts to increase the safety of blood products and continuous work in this area over the next few years, we have regained confidence in the public," he says, and proudly adds that almost 94% of the Québek population trusted Héma-Quebek at the beginning of 2008.
Dr. Decary, however, does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"We have witnessed in Europe many human cases of mad cow disease, new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease," says a woman who has been leading society since its inception in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could spread with blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of Krevere and Gélineau, according to which, when we do not know it and when it is at stake to spread a serious disease, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jacob's disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, we need to take exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we therefore refused blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that this disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode has shown us that following the precautionary principle made sense."
In 1999, there was a much more accurate technique on the market to detect HIV virus: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that allow the donor blood to detect the presence of the virus itself, not the presence of antibodies on which the tests used previously were based.
NAT tests have reduced the deafness that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our blood technicians may be exposed to the first viruses, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing and without knowing.
This improvement has significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
At the risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood, one of the 12 million people today is exposed.
"In other words, it means that before anyone gets HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission occurs through a blood product.
I think we can get or prescribe the blood transfusions needed to heal today in complete calm," says Héma-Quebek, chief of management.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of fertilising element might appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by insect sting.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," Dr. Decary continues, stressing that in addition to safe supplies, Hema-Quebec must also count on sufficient supplies.
"Needs are growing because the population is getting old.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has implications for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% of the Québecs allowed to donate."
Any healthy person aged at least 18 years, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can only donate blood once in 56 days, that means six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not on average accepted because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited the country where the mud winters are situated, they are excluded for one year.
"With this 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, donor network members need to be complemented in proportion to how they grow old and are no longer able to donate blood.
However, convincing people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so untangled today that we will only find an hour so we can donate blood," Francine Decary will.
With the annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Quebek, which also manages the only public blood bank from the cord in Québek.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, flows with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the contribution of our thousands of blood samples from the umbilical cord to the bank, and we assume that we will take over a thousand of them a year.
At the beginning of next year we should start offering them for transplants," Dr. Decary explains, who describes the blood collection program from the umbilical cord as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Quebec does not have the resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive programme to all hospitals in Québec.
