Trophy Psychology: Why are we spending more money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate goods.
Neurological and economic foundations of this famous - and seemingly irrational - behavior has been able to reveal to researchers in the field of neurology and the economy of the University of New York.
According to their study, published in Science magazine, people do not want to fall behind in the eBay auction type competition, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Research was using an experimental auction to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the second group participated in the auction, and the active areas of the brain of the experimental subjects were examined using the method of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, participants could win money, but at the auction game, whose important element is to truffle the other side, the whole under the brain’s skin, called stratum, began to function intensely when losing.
This brain area plays, in addition to many other functions, a role in the "self-replacement" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the price increase can be explained by an attempt to avoid a rapid reaction of the street.
To support their theory, members of the research team from a number of economies conducted a financial cross-sectional investigation.
Under different conditions, he was bidred against one partner by three groups.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was, and they made bets.
In addition, members of the next group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would get another $15 in reward.
The third group received $15, on the contrary, before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
So the difference between the two groups was that one was emphasized by the win and the other by the loss.
However, members of the "against losing" group were willing to go higher than they were in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the neurologist hypothesis.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
They have so far explained the phenomena that are visible in auctions of joy from victory and avoiding risk.
After the neurological imaging methods helped us solve the difference between these two theories so that we have now reached the third explanation," observed Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When to find a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the main causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 of them are treated, and the reason is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, there is a marked inflammation of the liver and jaundice, but the origins of the disease and their underlying diseases differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways, depending on the underlying diseases: hepatitis A and E intestinal systems (e.g. infected foods, water), hepatitis B, C, D, and other blood and body fluid viruses (sperm, urinary secret, saliva).
In any event, passengers should be protected by vaccination against virus A and B; there is no vaccine against virus C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, vomiting.
Then the skin and eye whites form yellowish, light stools and dark urine. The treatment may take two to three weeks.
Every year, millions of people worldwide will die from a more serious type of disease, liver cancer, and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only 1 out of every 10 infected people is treated medically.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most people infected with their disease don't even know, the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells occlusion, and so the first symptoms come in many cases up to 20-30 years.
It is therefore very important to prevent, in a timely manner, the implementation of a regular depravation.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more frequently than on average: among people who have undergone blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of subjects infected with chronic hepatitis C 200 million is estimated.
Since the disease may already prove a routine laboratory examination, a person should turn to a practical doctor if he notices any sign of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing infections and preventing cancer.
September 30th is the world day of hepatitis, which was organized for the first time by organizations representing the sick worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of their origin and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Who believes in God, doesn't it hurt so much?
According to recent research, belief in God works as an analgesic that could have eased the death of already Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how belief in God’s perception of pain affects a person, reported the British daily Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electrical shocks, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to eliminate much of the pain.
The technique used to examine the human brain has also shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain management.
Research is the first of a series of studies, attended by scientists, philosophers and theologians from various parts of the university.
The exact test was carried out by attaching to the left hand of the test subject a sparking instrument that produced electrical shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to scrupulously observe two paintings: the 17th century Sassoferrat's Virgin Mary and the 17th - century Lady with the food stamp of Leonard da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the study hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would arouse a certain state of piety among believers, while Da Vinci’s image was chosen because it was not too different from the first and seemed to them to be a soothing impression.
The test subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner, and during this time they received in four of the following sections 20 electroshocks, while separately following the image with a religious or general theme.
The Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe" as if they were taken care of" and "relaxed, filled with peace".
They felt 12 percent less pain as they watched the religious picture than they did Leonard’s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who has also participated in research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved by any powerful image even among atheists, only to find the right photograph.
"We would have to find an image that will be perceived very positively, from the position of mother or father," the psychologist said.
England's Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"Practification of faith should change and in many cases also change our personality," added Wright.
After such excellent results, it is only a question of what effect would it have on the regulation of the pain of believers if they showed them some Madonna from Leonard or a painter of a similar caliber.
Would it mean to look at the quality of the Virgin Mary to achieve even better results?
