An intelligent car mimics the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not for imitation of obstacles in the natural world?
Like a bee.
The initial strategic idea of a surprising project, presented at the Japanese fair CEATEC, was inspired by engineers from Nissan squires. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In cooperation with the Tokyo University, Nissan developed a biomimetic robotic control system such as BR23C, a robotic minia car equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping create a system that can eliminate all precipitation.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is in fact very similar to our safety protection package," explained Kazuhiro Doi, general director of the brand for the field of technological PR and research and development.
An important role is played by complex eyes that allow bees to see in all directions in a visual angle of more than 300 degrees.
Engineers were able to copy the function of a complex eye after the idea of a laser long-circuit.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters ahead of BR23C in the 180-degree field of vision, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately turns into an operation to prevent a collision.
The obstacle is detected during a fraction of a second, then the robotic car starts imitating the movements of the bee and turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision changes direction immediately.
Unlike any existing system, this evasive maneuver takes place in an entirely instinctive manner.
"If that were not the case, a robotic car could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety protection package, within which the collision is now considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what bees do to avoid other bees.
This process shall not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot go upwards, downwards or downwards, it can only be two-dimensional and only in a direction that can rotate the wheels.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees in avoiding them, only the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and slowing down was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, it is an important instinctive, intelligent response, not the ability to process, and less data storage.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to store and react through intuitive logic based on the data from previous manoeuvres, so it uses only a few kilobytes of memory all the time.
He doesn't need a memory with a giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing a technology that can be used for immediate avoidance, which is estimated by Nissan to be able to get into a series of manufactured cars within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, when avoided in the path of obstacles, would lead the motorist to the final goal.
