Finance Minister Henry Paulson announced the result of the compromise: "The programme will work and will be effective, but further steps must be taken."
The written form of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. in the evening of Washington time (then on Monday at 2 a.m. in Central European time), but no special rise in the stock exchanges did.
On the proposal for a legal norm, the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act, to be established by the programme, will be voted on Monday first by the House of Representatives, followed by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"With the progress achieved last night, we are pleased and very much appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The programme differs, however, from Bush's original administration proposal, in which it was intended that a total of $700 billion would be spent on the purchase of non-quality mortgage-backed securities.
Now it is possible to spend a maximum of half of the amount of 700 billion in the first round, which will be used immediately after the Congress decides on Monday, and the Ministry of Finance will purchase securities secured by mortgages that are considered to be inadequate, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will then depend on the President's decision.
The programme will be monitored by a special assembly, whose member will also be the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
The second half of $700 billion will depend on the Congress' next decision.
The Ministry of Finance may, within the meaning of the law, apply a combined tactic: it may at the same time purchase non-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, and in particular other "eatable" loans.
The ransom may take place as part of the auctions even directly, the competent representatives of the Ministry have informed them.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance scheme in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee of means of concern, for which companies will pay a price corresponding to the damage expected.
According to Henry Paulson, the law provides the necessary means to meet the urgent requirements of the US financial system, up to $700 billion, whether it is a large purchase of bad funds, insurance or the prevention of systemic risks associated with the collapse of one of the major monetary institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, the heads of the bank, who are in trouble and waiting for help from the state, can count on the government to reduce their distances - which is simply called a "golden parachute" in the overseas slang.
Only in certain cases will their payments be limited, and these restrictions will depend on the way in which the Ministry provides assistance.
The restriction essentially means that if the Ministry purchases during the auction, a tax deduction will be imposed on the gold parachutes if the fallen bank directors are not sent directly to the pension.
In the event of direct redemption of non-quality loans, the government will act aggressively in order to ensure that the money for management is not excessive.
It must be added that the existing agreements on gold falling will not change, the restrictions only concern new contracts, which should be another incentive to participate in the programme.
"This is the first case in American history where the legal restrictions on the remuneration of the Directors-General will be in force," commented the chairman of the Committee on Financial Services of the House of Representatives, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State in the banks participating in the programme will be entitled to a shareholding, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, as once the economy and its savings bank are on their feet, they can also profit from this transaction.
The proposal includes a proposal for the President to present to Congress in the next five years setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be reimbursed to taxpayers.
Of course, there were also voices on both sides expressing doubts about the plan.
"This is not what the American citizens have asked us to do, because this is what the taxpayers' dollars will not protect," declared a Republican congressman from California, Darrell Issa.
